-- Indian shares hit record high; exit polls point to Modi
-- By Abhishek Vishnoi
-- Tue May 13, 2014 06:06AM EDT
-- None



MUMBAI, May 13 (Reuters) - India's benchmark BSE index rose as much as 2.2 percent to a record high on Tuesday, surpassing the key psychological level of 24,000 points as companies focused on the domestic sector surged after exit polls showed the Bharatiya Janata Party and its allies winning a majority in the elections.

The BSE index <.BSESN> rose as much as 2.2 percent to hit a record high of 24,068.94. It ended up a provisional 1.36 percent. The NSE index <.NSEI> rose as much as 2.25 percent to hit a record high of 7,172.35. It ended 1.34 percent higher.